[3,5,6]. Furthermore, other studies have reported that sleep
patterns in children with ADHD may not be stable over
time, which could also account for some of the inconsis-
tencies [15].
Most of these studies have included children with ADHD
recruited from pediatric, neurology, or psychiatric clinics,
irrespective of whether they had a sleep problem, and com-
paring their sleep data to control subjects without ADHD.
There have been few studies reporting polysomnographic
ﬁndings in children with ADHD with complaints of sleep
disturbances [21,22]. The present objective was to describe
polysomnographic abnormalities in ADHD children who
also have symptoms of various sleep problems.

