## Methodology
Materials and Methods
We retrospectively analyzed the polysomnographic data of children
with ADHD who had undergone a sleep study in our sleep laboratory dur-
ing the year 2005 for various sleep-related complaints, including difﬁculty
falling asleep, snoring, and frequent arousals from sleep. The diagnosis of
ADHD was clinically based on DSM-IV [23] and was made by board-cer-
tiﬁed pediatric neurologists.
An attended overnight sleep study was conducted using digital poly-
somnography equipment (Rembrandt Medcare–Embla, Broomﬁeld, CO).
All polysomnographies were performed using simultaneous pressure trans-
ducer and thermistor for nasal ﬂow, piezoelectric chest and abdominal
belts, and end-tidal CO2 monitoring, along with pulse oximetry, snore mi-
crophone, two leg channels, chin electromyogram, electroencephalogram,
electrocardiogram, and simultaneous video monitoring.
Age, sex, and body mass index were assessed. Detailed sleep parameters
measured included total sleep time, sleep and rapid eye movement latency,
