## Results
Results of subjective studies, however, have not been
corroborated by more objective investigations using poly-
somnography or actigraphy. Polysomnography studies [7-
20] have yielded inconsistent results (summarized in Table
1). A recent meta-analysis of polysomnography studies
failed to ﬁnd any signiﬁcant differences in sleep architec-
ture or sleep disordered breathing between children with
ADHD and control subjects. Periodic limb movements in
sleep, however, were signiﬁcantly more common among
children with ADHD than in control subjects [5]. Another
meta-analysis suggested that children with ADHD have
higher daytime sleepiness, more movements in sleep, and
higher apnea hypopnea index compared with control sub-
jects [6]. This lack of agreement of results among various
studies may to some extent be due to methodologic
